description: Toms Keeps His Promise is the story of a Mexican boy who is the son of the best cheese-maker in his village but who dreams of becoming a rich nobleman on horseback, complete with a silver saddle and silver spurs, a man who has the respect of all the village. Toms discovers what a seemingly impossible challenge that the real world can thrust on him, however, when his injured and bedridden father calls on him to take his place as the flute player and leader for a 500-year-old ceremony called el juego del volador, the flying pole dance. His task is to play the traditional tunes and dance the traditional dance, both of which he knows, but now he must climb to the top of an 80-foot pole and play and dance on a revolving platform as four village men in their feathered costumes perform acrobatic tricks as they swing slowly to the ground. After just ten days of practice, Toms bravely fulfills the task his father had placed on his young shoulders and earns the respect of the village... The book is an excellent account of an ancient Mexican cultural tradition, but it also embodies the human universal of the value of bravely undertaking and ultimately completing a seemingly impossible taska lesson well worth learning for children and adults alike... - Alan M. Schroder, Senior Production Editor, University of Arizona Press, retired The language is deliciously rich and flows as smoothly as the voladores fly. The story uniquely incorporates both English and Spanish, making it a perfect selection for teaching a second language and the intricate illustrations bring such authenticity. - Jennifer Dutson, M.A. Ed., Elementary Educator/International Schools, Children's Museum of Oro Valley, AZ It shows how Tomas has perseverance to do the Flying Pole Dance when other people, and even himself, doubt that he can do it. He perseveres and manages the task, despite how hard it is and he doesn't think he can do it. - Ravi, age 11
